People smoking hookah were blowing the smoke on my face while I was trying to enjoy my delicious $2 taco and sip on my $2 margarita (Let's just say it's what you can expect from a $2 drink😑 but it's not terrible). By the way the tacos were really good! They were a mix of cabbage some green sauce and very tasty meat - I was impressed and wondered how the rest of their food must taste?? They look really good in their pictures. We also had the chips with guacamole and they did not disappoint. The chips were freshly made and the guacamole was delicious (a tiny bit spicy). The waitresses were very accommodating and nice, although getting their attention was a little bit of a struggle at times. The only problem I had with this place is that it is way too loud. Happy hour is a time to mingle while ur having drinks and appetizers, I couldn't hear a word anyone was saying, including the waitress. I was screaming half of my time there. There was a live DJ with really good music, but honestly I was getting agitated from how loud it was. It felt like like I was at club, but no one was dancing. There was some small amount of dancing later on, in the evening, but that only lasted for like 20 mins. Overall I woud like to come again, but I am hesitant to come on a Tuesday. Overall this may not be a place to have a conversation unless you know sign language.

We were so excited to see Barchaa open as there are still few nicer restaurants within walking distance.  Overall friendly yet seemingly inexperienced staff and average food.  As they're in their second month they still have some kinks to work out and I'm sure will continue to refine the menu.  We'll give it another shot for brunch sometime soon as I'm really pulling for this place.  Ambiance - overall an attractive space decked out in exposed brick and reclaimed wood like many a place in Bushwick.  We came in on a Sunday at 8PM and the music was blaring so loud we had to sit on the same side of a 4 top to hear each other.  This was a bad way to start things off.  The music was also being played from an unmanned turntable so songs would end and someone would have to hop back to get another one going.  kind of weird.  Food - we ordered just apps & a salad so it's possible we didn't try the best on the menu.  The meal started with some little friend breadstrips and a spicy mayo sauce as complimentary.  Really tasty and a nice touch though the sauce came in a to-go plastic cup feeling a bit cheap.  We then had the grilled lettuce salad (basically BLT), wings and the ceveche with shrimp and scallops.  All the protien s we fresh and well cooked.  Where they fell down was on sauces.  There was a ton of BBQ sauce glommed on the wings that was really sugary.  Way too much dressing on the salad and the ceveche was way more sugary than we personally enjoy.  Drinks - I got one drink called the Hermenia that was a mango base.  It was delicious!  Service - lots of little things showed inexperience: - 30 seconds after we arrived a server brought us someone else's drink order - our server appologized that our waters too so long (they didn't) saying they were very busy earlier as an excuse. - we were seated in the back and half way through our meal they asked if we wanted to move to the front of the restaurant.  Felt strange and we were left wondering if they wanted to look more full - my water was cleared when the plates were cleared at the end. - no pen in the check book  The only other thing I'd add is the silver wear is about as cheap as it gets.  I hope they reinvest in a different set once the place is established.  I'd love to check this place out on a Friday or Saturday night as I'm sure it's a super fun Latin vibe.  As you can see from the above a lot to work out but good potential as well to become a neighborhood favorite.

Coconut flan for dessert topped with whipped cream and maraschino cherry. We knew we were in for something good when they brought these delicate bread stick appetizers with an amazing dipping sauce. Great spot.
Good vibes and good food! Must try
Cozy Place, Good Food.
